solutions.content:
Key point: store temp value & move terms to the right( why don't we change the value right of "=")
For those who only needs the solution, go to part IV directly. 
If you have any questions or suggestions, feel free to write below.

**I. Introduction**
	To better explain what I did, please allow me to introduce a new operator "~", which means literally combine two numbers. For instance, 1~3 = 13, 67~89 = 6789, -7~8 = -78( pay extra attention to this! ). Noticed that it's different from x*10+y, we need to write a specific function implementing this operator, see function "combine" for details.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/86455c2f-4687-435e-8aaa-dd19737bdf3d_1619089354.4731524.png)


So for a string containing n digits, there are n-1 blanks to fill and there are 4 possibilities for every blank, so the total possibilities is 4^(n-1). 

**II. A Straight-forward solution and why it results in TLE**
To try all the possibilities, we can easily devise a solution using recursion: try + - * ~ one by one in each blank and move forward. Unfortunately, this solution give you TLE because you only calculate the value after you fully build the expression, which involves too much redundant calculation. 

To get some intuition, take this half finished equation (left part) as an example

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/080acc6f-780f-45f4-8821-e8a2aff181c3_1619089502.8828244.png)


There're two blanks left, so there're 4^2=16 possibilities left. So1*2+3~4 would be calculate 16 times. 



**III. A revised solution**
Shown as above, redundant computation gives you TLE in return. A naive approach is to calculate the “partial answer” or “value so far”, that is, the output of the part we have finished. 


For instance, in the equation given above, we could directly compute the value of 1*2+34 = 36 and use this "value so far" for future attempts. 

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/a94b1185-1682-4c51-80be-cf5cc1135f03_1619089538.4591494.png)



Actaully, why don't we move this 36 to the right part since no matter what operator between 5 and 8 is, the "value so far" is fixed.
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/5c55a2e1-9b0d-4a9c-a350-d4e8b918f0b2_1619089570.8583777.png)


Further look at the following equation, we find that once we decide to use "+" between two digits, the value of the part left of "+" is always fixed and we should move this part to the right.
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ed0d13c0-ed78-45b6-b1e2-b774b5e29e63_1619081561.0559442.png)
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/069edc53-a92a-4e29-a330-1b9e799df708_1619081714.311086.png)

Actually, we can also do this when we decide to use "-" for the same reason. The only thing we need to care is to keep the "-" inside of the right part.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/44b5ae95-82a8-450d-bd36-3d4b16286ec1_1619082005.560652.png)

Then the question come: what if we decide to use * between two digits?
Indeed, we cannot move the left part to the right in this circumstance, what's worse, we cannot even calculate the left part because of "~". 
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/d154422f-a2bd-4c07-97dd-7f6100bd2ef1_1619082782.6420016.png)


Assume we merge "5*8" into 40, just like the picture shows. If we decide to use "~" between 8 and 9, them the 40 would be  meaningless and there's no way to fix it (the solution leetcode gives couldn't handle this). In order to handle this, some special tricks are used. The following content talks about how to handle * and ~.

We utilize two "registers" reg1, reg2 (reg1 is set to be the first digit and reg2 is initialized to 1) to the save two factors and a special "pointer" pointing at one of them, telling us which one is "active". The pointer points to reg1 from the begining. Let's start with an example:
From the very begining, reg1 = the first digit = 5, reg2 = 1, ptr = reg1. 

First blank:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/cde1f912-6be2-46aa-8b55-99c98b167770_1619084518.2493339.png)
We decide to use "*" between 5 and 8: we update the two registers in a fixed way: reg1 = reg1 * reg2, reg2 = next digits. Change the ptr to reg2. Now the reg1 = 5 * 1 = 5,  reg2 = 8,  ptr = reg2


Second blank:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/050361bf-df4a-48c9-a281-97857ec75bc6_1619084858.448591.png)
In the second blank, we choose * anew. Again, update two registers with the same rule and change the ptr to 2(not changed). After that, 
reg1 = 5 * 8 = 40    reg2 = 9  ptr = reg2


Thrid blank:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/a4037de7-6378-4a5e-8306-10119c915ecc_1619086227.804287.png)
Here we decide to use "-". As we said before, move the left part to the right and the left part is given by reg1 * reg2 = 360. Then we change reg1 to next digit -6; set reg2 = 1, and set ptr back to reg1. The equation becomes:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/d7a86855-04fe-41a5-82f1-77320ad01271_1619086504.715896.png)


Fifth blank:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/fe1c4598-a9db-424a-bf42-ec64182b48ad_1619086668.9973226.png)
If we choose "~" for this blank, we need to merge the next digit (2 here) with the register pointer by ptr, that is, reg1.
Then we have: reg1=  -62  reg2 = 1  ptr = reg1.

...

So in a nutshell, 
when we use "+" or "-", we should move the left part to the right by set right -= reg1 * reg2, and set reg1=reg2=1, ptr = reg1;
when we use "*", set reg1 *= reg2, and reg2 = next digits, ptr = reg2;
when we use "~", set the reg? pointed by ptr to combine(reg?, next digit).

In the end, if we find reg1 * reg2 = right, this combination of operators is valid.

**IV. The final solution**
	This solution owns nice performance.
	![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f79db340-220c-45e8-9511-d9215c8c31ce_1613575140.6618643.png)



```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<string> res;

    long long combine(long long a, long long b){
        /**
         * you need to make sure: a ! = 0
         * combine(54,8) = 548 combine(-42,8) = -428
        */
        bool negative = (a<0);
        a = abs(a);
        return (negative)? -(a*10 + b) : (a*10 + b);
    }

    void handle(const string& num, const long long& target, const int& index, 
				const long long B1, const long long B2,const int ptr, char* op_rec){
        if(index == num.size()-1){
            // reach the end
            if(target - B1*B2 == 0){
                // this is a feasible solution! Store it in res.
                string temp = to_string(num[0]-'0');
                for(int i=0;i<num.size()-1;++i){
                    if(op_rec[i] == '~')
                        temp += num[i+1];
                    else {
                        temp += op_rec[i];
                        temp += num[i+1];  
                    }
                }
                res.push_back(temp);
            }
            // nope, do nothing.
            return;
        }
        long long next_target;
        int digit = num[index + 1] - '0';
        // not the end
        // "+"
        op_rec[index] = '+';
        next_target = target - B1 * B2;
        handle(num,next_target,index+1,digit,1,1,op_rec);

        // "-"
        op_rec[index] = '-';
        //next_target = target - B1 * B2; same as above
        handle(num,next_target,index+1,-digit,1,1,op_rec);

        // "*"
        op_rec[index] = '*';
        handle(num,target,index+1,B1*B2,digit,2,op_rec);

        // "~"
        op_rec[index] = '~';
        long long B1_copy = B1;
        long long B2_copy = B2;
        if(ptr == 1 && B1 != 0)
            // you cannot combine 0 and 9 to 09
            B1_copy = combine(B1_copy,digit);
        else if(ptr == 2 & B2 != 0)
            B2_copy = combine(B2_copy,digit);
        else
            return;
        handle(num,target,index+1,B1_copy,B2_copy,ptr,op_rec);
    }

    vector<string> addOperators(string num, int target) {
        if(num.empty())
            return res;
        char *op_rec = new char[num.size()-1];
        int index = 0;
        long long B1 = num[0] - '0', B2 = 1;
