Not even going to lie to you, this one's Hard.  See LC solution tab for basic approach.

```
var addOperators = function(num, target) {
  const res = [];
  backtrack();
  return res;

  function backtrack(ind = 0, tot = 0, exp = '', curNum = 0, befMult = 0) {
    //If at end and curNum is still a value or we didn't find the total
    //Return because it's not a correct solution path.
    if (ind === num.length && (curNum || tot !== target)) return;

    //If at end and total === target, push answer and return.
    if (ind === num.length && tot === target) return res.push(exp);

    //num[ind]-0 converts string at current index to a number.
    //*10 grow cur.  Two lines below just give possible number permutations.
    //Note that all recursive calls other than this one set curNum = 0.
    //This one calls with curNum = next.  What is next though?
    //First time this runs, next = 0 * 10 + (num[ind]-0).  Let's say we get 1 in num[ind],
    //0*10 + 1 = 1.  Then we invoke backtrack again, but we only increment index and 
    //pass in our 1.  Now, next time, next = 1 * 10 + num[idx].  Let's say 5 this time.
    //This sets next to 15.  In this way, we have built up 15 from 1,5.  Combinations
    //of all the above are now in recursive paths.  The if(next) ensures we aren't recursing
	//down erroneous paths - Ie. '10122' could lead us to build up '01', '012', '0122' which 
	//just turns out to be the same as if we skipped the 0 and started building up at the 1.
    const next = curNum * 10 + (num[ind]-0);
    if (next) backtrack(ind+1, tot, exp, next, befMult);

    //Here we add.  We start with adding because if expression is empty (as in when invoked),
    //we can't just subtract or multiply out of the gate.  We need to get at least one number in expression
    //before doing those operations, else '-5' or '*5' is going to end up at the start of our exp.
    //Here, we can check if there's expression length or not, if not, we just add next num as a string (+'').
    //This is allowed because 0 + num still equals the num.  0 - 5 doesn't equal the original num, and 0*5
    //certainly doesn't either.  Ergo, we have to add first in order to attain a valid starting number to recurse on.
	//If total = -5 or 0 after just having a '5' in expression, our expression and total are out of sync.  Adding first
	//avoids this issue.
    backtrack(ind+1, tot + next, exp.length ? exp+"+"+next : next + '', 0, next);

    //If we are in a recursion level After initial invocation, there will be exp.length.
    //Now that we know we already have at least one num in the exp, we can use
    //the other operators to alter total / expression.
    if (exp.length) {
      backtrack(ind+1, tot - next, exp+"-"+next, 0, -next);

      //This is the trickiest part of the problem imo.  If you could just use eval(exp) every time to 
      //calculate total not on-the-fly, it's Way easier.  Butttttt, I suppose when you get a number
      //like 999879687348598, and have expressions like '9+9*9-8*7-9+6-8*3-4-8*5+9-8'...
      //and you're evaluating on Every permutation / recursion level... That is a little taxing.  
      //Keeping track of the total Before multiplying last is very clever and definitely the right way 
      //to do it, but that's not an easy intuitive leap to make imo.  Hopefully my future interviewer's fine 
      //with the terrible eval() runtime or generous with the hints. lol...  Because I'm not sure I'd get
      //this without at least a nudge.
      backtrack(ind+1, tot - befMult + (befMult * next), exp+"*"+next, 0, (befMult * next));
    }
  }
