# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
This solution aims to move all the zeros in a given vector nums to the end of the vector while preserving the relative order of the non-zero elements. Let's break down the solution step by step:

Initialize variables:

n stores the size of the vector nums.
start represents the index where the next non-zero element should be placed.
end represents the index of the last element in the vector.
mid is used to iterate through the vector from the beginning to the end.
Start the while loop: The loop continues until mid reaches the index of the last element (end).

Check if the element at the current index mid is non-zero:

If nums[mid] is not equal to 0, it means it is a non-zero element.
In this case, we need to move this non-zero element to the front of the vector.
To achieve this, we swap the elements at indices start and mid, effectively moving the non-zero element to the position indicated by start.
Increment start by 1: After swapping the elements, we increment start to prepare for the next non-zero element that we might encounter later in the vector.

Increment mid by 1: Regardless of whether the element at mid was non-zero or zero, we always increment mid by 1 to move on to the next element in the vector.

Repeat steps 3-5 until mid exceeds end: This loop continues until we have iterated through all the elements in the vector.

After the loop finishes, all the non-zero elements will be placed at the beginning of the vector, and all the zeros will be at the end. The relative order of the non-zero elements will remain the same as in the original vector.

It's worth noting that this solution operates in-place, meaning it modifies the original vector without using any extra space.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(1)
